<HEADLINE>
TAIWAN DELEGATION BRIEFS FISU ON PLAN TO HOST 2011 UNIVERSIADE
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Turin,  Italy,  Jan.  16 (CNA) 01/16/07  21:52:24 (By Huang Kwan-
chun and Luis Huang)
</P>
<P>
A Taiwan delegation delivered a briefing  Tuesday  to  the
International University  Sports Federation (FISU) on the
Kaohsiung city government's plan to host the 2011 Summer
Universiade.
</P>
<P>
The briefing was delivered by Chen Chuan-show, chairman of the
National Council for Physical Fitness and Sports, Chen Pei-chi, a
delegation member, and Lee Tien-jen, president of the Chinese
Taipei University Sports Federation (CTUSF) , with Lee handing
over a financial blueprint to FISU Chairman George Killian.
</P>
<P>
Chen told the FISU's Executive Commission that Taiwan has been
preparing to host the World University Games for 10 years and
that it is Kaohsiung City's third attempt to obtain the hosting
right for the event.
</P>
<P>
Claiming that the city's bid has the support of "all sectors in
Taiwan, " Chen voiced the hope the Executive Commission will
grant Taiwan the hosting right.
</P>
<P>
Following Chen's speech, a short film concerning Kaohsiung's
urban development, software and hardware construction, sports and
recreational facilities, as well as folk culture and tourism, was
aired to give the commissioners a better understanding of the
harbor city's current situation.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan delegation's  report won acclaim from all FISU
commissioners, while Killian presented a medal to the delegation
on behalf of the FISU in recognition of the country's
enthusiastic participation in the federation's activities.
</P>
<P>
Kaohsiung has been selected by the FISU as one of the five
official candidate cities to host the 2011 event. The other four
candidates are Shenzhen in China, Kazan in Russia, Poznan in
Poland and Murcia in Spain.
</P>
<P>
The city, which will host the 2009 World Games, made its last
unsuccessful bid to host the Universiade in 2003.
</P>
